        {
            "id": "index_error",
            "elements": [
                {
                    "type": "heading",
                    "content": "Handling Errors",
                    "properties": {
                        "level": 2
                    }
                },
                {
                    "type": "text",
                    "content": "**Be careful!** If you try to find a value that doesn't exist in the list, `index()` will cause an error."
                },
                {
                    "type": "code",
                    "content": "colors = [\"red\", \"green\", \"blue\"]\nposition = colors.index(\"yellow\")",
                    "properties": {
                        "language": "python",
                        "output": "Error: 'yellow' is not in list"
                    }
                },
                {
                    "type": "text",
                    "content": "Since `\"yellow\"` is not in the list, `index()` raises an error."
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "id": "checking_before_index",
            "elements": [
                {
                    "type": "text",
                    "content": "To avoid errors, you can check if the value exists using the `in` operator before calling `index()`."
                },
                {
                    "type": "code",
                    "content": "fruits = [\"apple\", \"banana\", \"orange\"]\n\nif \"grape\" in fruits:\n    position = fruits.index(\"grape\")\n    print(f\"Found at {position}\")\nelse:\n    print(\"Grape not found\")",
                    "properties": {
                        "language": "python",
                        "output": "Grape not found"
                    }
                },
                {
                    "type": "text",
                    "content": "By checking with `in` first, we avoid the error and handle the missing value gracefully."
                }
            ]
        },
